Master Prompt — Minecraft Java Edition (Forge 1.21.1) In-Game OpenGL Overlay Menu + ESP System
Target Game: Minecraft Java Edition, running on the JVM via Forge mod loader (version 1.21.1). The game uses LWJGL + OpenGL for rendering. This project hooks OpenGL's wglSwapBuffers for the overlay. Game data is accessed via JNI + JVMTI since Minecraft is a Java application — we attach to the running JVM from native C++ code and call Java methods / read Java fields to extract entity positions, health, names, etc.

CAUTION

Forge uses TransformingClassLoader, NOT the bootstrap classloader. Standard JNIEnv::FindClass() will fail for most Minecraft classes. You MUST use JVMTI GetLoadedClasses to discover Forge's classloader, then call ClassLoader.loadClass() on it for all subsequent class lookups. This is the #1 cause of "class not found" errors.

1 — PROJECT OVERVIEW & GOALS
Build a Windows DLL (C++20, x64) that is injected into the Minecraft Java Edition process (javaw.exe) at runtime. Once loaded, the DLL must:

Hook OpenGL's wglSwapBuffers (from opengl32.dll) using MinHook.
Initialize Dear ImGui (OpenGL3 + Win32 backend) inside that hook so every frame an overlay is composited on top of Minecraft.
Render a modern tabbed menu (toggled with INSERT key) containing cheat-module controls: checkboxes, sliders, color pickers, and custom toggle switches. The menu title should read "NULL CLIENT // Forge 1.21.1".
Implement an ESP system that draws 2D bounding boxes, health bars, player/mob names, and distance text for every valid nearby entity.
Clean up gracefully (unhook, destroy ImGui context, restore original WndProc) when the user presses DELETE.
Critical: Minecraft is a Java application. All game-data retrieval is done via JNI (Java Native Interface) with JVMTI for class discovery. The DLL attaches to the running JVM inside javaw.exe, bootstraps Forge's classloader via JVMTI, then uses that classloader for all subsequent 
findClass
 calls.

Obfuscation Note: Forge 1.21.1 uses Mojang's official mappings ("mojmap"), so class/method/field names are human-readable (e.g., Entity.getX(), LivingEntity.getHealth()). All class/method/field name strings should be centralized in a single 
mappings.h
 file so they can be easily updated.

